You can update a column of type SET in MySQL using the following syntax:

```sql
UPDATE table_name
SET column_name = column_name + 'new_value'
WHERE condition;
```

However, when you add a new value to a SET column, MySQL will automatically add the new value to the existing ones. You don't need to specify the existing values.

Here is an example:

```sql
CREATE TABLE test (
  id INT AUTO_INCREMENT,
  flags SET DEFAULT 'a,b',
  PRIMARY KEY (id)
);

INSERT INTO test (flags) VALUES ('a');
INSERT INTO test (flags) VALUES ('b');
INSERT INTO test (flags) VALUES ('a,b');

UPDATE test
SET flags = flags + 'c'
WHERE id = 1;

SELECT * FROM test;
```

In this example, the `flags` column will be updated to `'a,b,c'` for the row with `id = 1`.

Note that if you try to update the column with a value that is not a valid SET value (i.e., a value that contains duplicate values or a value that is not a single character), MySQL will raise an error.

Also, note that the `SET` data type in MySQL has a limit of 64 possible values.

